'''Christian Salem''' (born 15 July 1995) is a professional [[Australian rules football]]er playing for the [[Melbourne Football Club]] in the [[Australian Football League]] (AFL). A [[Australian rules football positions#Half-back line|defender]], {{convert|1.81|m|ftin}} tall and weighing {{convert|83|kg}}, Salem plays primarily as a [[Half-back line#Half-back flank|half-back flanker]], with the ability to push into the [[Centre line (football)#Wing|midfield]] and [[Australian rules football positions#Half-forward line|forward line]]. He was recognised as a talented footballer at a young age when he represented Victoria at under 12 level. He played top-level football early when he played in both the [[TAC Cup]] and [[AFL Under 18 Championships]] as a [[TAC Cup#Age eligibility|bottom-aged player]]. His achievements as a junior saw him selected with the ninth pick in the [[2013 AFL draft]] by the Melbourne Football Club and he made his AFL debut during the 2014 season.

==Early life==
Salem was born to Alex and Mary Salem, and is of [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]] descent with his father being born in [[Lebanon]].<ref name=descent>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2013-05-03/footy-in-the-blood|title=Footy in the blood for young Salem|last=Twomey|first=Callum|date=3 May 2013|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=[[Bigpond]]|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> His talent was recognised from a young age when he received state selection in the under-12 Victorian side.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/afl/afl-news/afl-draft-will-split-four-close-friends-and-families-20131117-2xp4j.html|title=AFL draft will split four close friends and families|last=Quayle|first=Emma|date=18 November 2013|work=[[The Age]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> He attended [[Brighton Grammar School|Brighton Grammar]] and played with the [[Robert Shaw (footballer)|Robert Shaw]] coached first XVIIIs side from year nine, generally playing against year twelves.<ref name=heraldsundraft>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/collingwood-circles-midfield-dynamo-christian-salem/story-fnau1fjg-1226756073229|title=Collingwood circles midfield dynamo Christian Salem|last=Clark|first=Jay|date=8 November 2013|work=[[Herald Sun]]|publisher=[[News Corp Australia]]|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref>

Salem played his junior career with the [[Hampton Rovers Football Club]] and played for the [[Sandringham Dragons]] in the [[TAC Cup]] in both 2012 and 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hamptonrovers.com.au/news/news.php?newsid=1888|title=Salem, Amon and Hunt picked up in AFL Draft|date=22 November 2013|work=HamptonRovers.com.au|publisher=CV Media|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> He was selected to play for Victoria Metro in the [[2012 AFL Under 18 Championships]] as a bottom-aged player and played in the winning final, kicking two goals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2012-07-04/vics-victorious|title=Vics victorious|last=Guthrie|first=Ben|date=4 July 2012|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> He received a scholarship through the [[Australian Institute of Sport|AIS-AFL Academy]] as part of their level two squad in the 2012 intake,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsportspulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=3020-3020-0-0-0&sID=69677&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=21408378|title=AIS-AFL Academy Kicks Off|date=29 November 2011|work=TACcup.com.au|publisher=Fox Sports Pulse|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref> and travelled to Europe for two weeks in 2013.<ref name=descent/> He received mid-year state honours for the second consecutive year and played for Victoria Metro in the [[2013 AFL Under 18 Championships]].<ref name=AFLdraftprofile>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2013-10-25/27-days-to-the-draft-meet-christian-salem|title=27 days to the draft: Meet gun prospect Christian Salem|last=Twomey|first=Callum|date=25 October 2013|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref>

Salem was rated highly heading into the [[2013 AFL draft]] and was predicted to be drafted inside the top ten due to his decision making and kicking precision, in addition, he drew comparisons to [[Luke Hodge]], [[Nick Dal Santo]] and [[Dan Hannebery]].<ref name=heraldsundraft/><ref name=AFLdraftprofile/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/game-development/nab-afl-rising-star-program/u18s/afl-academy-player-profiles|title=AFL-AIS Academy Player Profiles|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref>

==AFL career==
[[File:Christian Salem 2015.JPG|thumb|left|150px|Christian Salem at training in July 2015]]
Salem was recruited by the [[Melbourne Football Club]] with their first selection and ninth overall in the [[2013 AFL draft#2013 national draft|2013 national draft]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.melbournefc.com.au/news/2013-11-21/salem-eager-to-make-an-impact|title=Salem eager to make an impact|last=Burgan|first=Matt|date=21 November 2013|work=MelbourneFC.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> During the pre-season, he suffered from a [[thyroid]] issue which saw him lose six kilograms in the month following the draft.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2016-05-24/health-issue-resurfaces-for-demon-defender|title=Health issue resurfaces for Demon defender|last=Guthrie|first=Ben|date=24 May 2016|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> He played the start of the season in the [[Victorian Football League]] (VFL)  for Melbourne's [[Australian Football League reserves affiliations|affiliate team]], the [[Casey Scorpions]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2014-04-20/around-the-leagues-bellchambers-back|title=Around the state leagues: Salem pushes for debut, Brock in form|last=King|first=Travis|date=20 April 2014|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> and after strong form in the VFL, including a thirty-two possession game in the VFL round three match against {{VFL Fra}} at [[Frankston Park]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2014-04-28/salems-lot|title=Salem's lot for new Demon on debut|last=Guthrie|first=Ben|date=28 April 2014|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> he made his AFL debut a week later in the thirty-one point loss against {{AFL Syd}} at the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]] in round six.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/afl/demons-unleash-christian-salem-20140424-zqz0f.html|title=Demons unleash Christian Salem|last=Murnane|first=Matt|date=24 April 2014|work=The Age|publisher=Fairfax Media|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> In his seventh match, Salem was pivotal in Melbourne's comeback victory against {{AFL Ess}} in round thirteen,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/afl/afl-news/late-christian-salem-goal-leads-demons-to-stirring-comeback-victory-over-essendon-20140615-zs8ol.html|title=Late Christian Salem goal leads Demons to stirring comeback victory over Essendon|last=Cherny|first=Daniel|date=15 June 2014|work=The Age|publisher=Fairfax Media|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> after marking the ball thirty metres directly in front of goal, he kicked the winning goal with nineteen seconds left in the match, giving Melbourne a one-point lead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2014-06-15/salem-the-hero-|title=Salem's cool head saves the day for Demons|last=Phelan|first=Jennifer|date=15 June 2014|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> He finished his debut season with twelve matches<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.melbournefc.com.au/news/2014-11-05/salem-relishes-first-year-taste|title=Salem relishes first year taste|last=Burgan|first=Matt|date=5 November 2014|work=MelbourneFC.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> and senior ''[[Herald Sun]]'' football writer, Jay Clark, wrote he had the potential to become one of Melbourne's best players.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/melbourne-blueprint-demons-believe-theyre-setup-to-succeed-in-2015/news-story/debe2eac82381d0e6f59a35906ac9798?sv=df18d512c7d52c32d987a05ad638574|title=Melbourne Blueprint: Demons believe they’re setup to succeed in 2015|last=Clark|first=Jay|date=16 November 2014|work=Herald Sun|publisher=News Corp Australia|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref>

After playing his debut season in the forward line and a majority of matches as the substitute,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.melbournefc.com.au/news/2015-02-09/salem-ready-to-make-his-mark|title=Salem ready to make his mark|last=Burgan|first=Matt|date=9 February 2015|work=MelbourneFC.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> Salem changed positions in 2015 and played predominantly on the [[Australian rules football positions#Half-back line|half-back line]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.melbournefc.com.au/news/2015-02-19/salem-relishes-halfback-opportunity|title=Salem relishes half-back opportunity|last=Burgan|first=Matt|date=19 February 2015|work=MelbourneFC.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/teams/melbourne/nathan-jones-hails-melbourne-young-gun-christian-salem/news-story/825573956d983eea55aa19f8795584c4?sv=97b02cecb9a861d05d2a5f988a900128|title=Nathan Jones hails Melbourne young gun Christian Salem|last=Edmund|first=Sam|date=15 March 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=News Corp Australia|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> Playing the first seven matches of the season, he injured his hamstring in the round seven loss to {{AFL Haw}} and was initially ruled out for a month,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2015-05-20/salems-lot-sees-demon-defender-out-for-a-month|title=Salem's lot: Demon defender out for a month|last=Phelan|first=Jason|date=20 May 2015|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> however, after injuring his other hamstring,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.melbournefc.com.au/news/2015-06-11/salem-to-miss-another-month|title=Salem to miss another month|last=Burgan|first=Matt|date=11 June 2015|work=MelbourneFC.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> he ultimately missed two months and returned from injury playing in the VFL in round sixteen,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.melbournefc.com.au/news/2015-08-15/sick-salem-bailed-out-by-rohan|title=Sick Salem bailed out by Rohan|last=Burgan|first=Matt|date=15 August 2015|work=MelbourneFC.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> before returning to the senior side in round twenty-one in the twenty-three point loss against {{AFL Car}} at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.melbournefc.com.au/news/2015-08-20/salem-and-stretch-return-for-round-21|title=Salem and Stretch return for round 21|last=Harrington|first=Anna|date=20 August 2015|work=MelbourneFC.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> He played the remainder of the season and finished with ten matches overall.<ref name=afltables>{{cite web|url=http://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/C/Christian_Salem.html|title=Christian Salem|publisher=AFL Tables|accessdate=13 May 2014}}</ref>

After declaring his intentions to play in the [[Follower (Australian rules football)|midfield]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.melbournefc.com.au/news/2015-10-01/midfield-the-aim-for-salem|title=Midfield the aim for Salem|last=Burgan|first=Matt|last2=Lewis|first2=Georgina|date=1 October 2015|work=MelbourneFC.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/afl-2016-season-players-set-to-switch-roles-and-positions-at-your-club/news-story/d58ddac3c979b7d0869149c1181dde8d|title=AFL 2016 season: Players set to switch roles and positions at your club|last=Waterworth|first=Ben|date=2 February 2016|work=[[Fox Sports (Australia)]]|publisher=News Corp Australia|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> Salem retained his spot on the half-back line whilst also playing on the [[Centre line (football)#Wing|wing]] and prior to the season, he was labelled as one of the players who could have a breakout season by AFL Media journalist, Ben Guthrie.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2016-03-02/breaking-out-the-players-set-to-explode|title=Breaking out: The players set to explode in 2016|last=Guthrie|first=Ben|date=2 March 2016|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> Entrusted with the [[kick-in]]s for the season<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/afl/afl-news/melbournes-christian-salem-is-kicking-on--and-in-20160314-gnigo3.html|title=Melbourne's Christian Salem is kicking on - and in|last=Quayle|first=Emma|date=14 March 2016|work=The Age|publisher=Fairfax Media|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> due to his elite kicking skills,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2016-04-02/salems-lot-how-the-demons-rebuilt-their-defensive-pillar|title=Salem's lot: How the Demons rebuilt their running defender|last=Guthrie|first=Ben|date=2 April 2016|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> Salem played the first six matches of the season before suffering from a [[concussion]] as a result of a head clash during the thirty-nine point loss against {{AFL StK}} at [[Docklands Stadium|Etihad Stadium]] in round six.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2016-05-04/concussion-claims-dees-duo|title=Concussion claims Dees duo ahead of Gold Coast clash|last=Malcolm|first=Alex|date=4 May 2016|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> He returned two weeks later for the thirty-two point loss against the {{AFL WB}} at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.melbournefc.com.au/news/2016-05-13/melbourne-makes-just-one-change|title=Melbourne makes just one change|last=Burgan|first=Matt|date=13 May 2016|work=MelbourneFC.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> After being omitted the next week and playing for Casey in the VFL, a recurrence of his thyroid issue would see him miss two months of any form of football,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.melbournefc.com.au/news/2016-05-27/no-timeframe-on-salems-return-roos|title=No timeframe on Salem’s return: Roos|last=Burgan|first=Matt|date=27 May 2016|work=MelbourneFC.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> and he returned for Casey when he played against {{VFL Cob}} in round seventeen of the VFL season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.melbournefc.com.au/news/2016-07-29/casey-scorpions-teams-round-17|title=Casey Scorpions teams: round 17|last=Burgan|first=Matt|date=29 July 2016|work=MelbourneFC.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> After playing the next three weeks in the VFL, he returned to the senior side for the final match of the year in the 111-point loss against {{AFL Gee}} at [[Kardinia Park (stadium)|Simonds Stadium]], which saw him finish with eight matches for the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.melbournefc.com.au/news/2016-08-25/team-selection-round-23|title=Salem returns for season closer|last=Lewis|first=Georgina|date=25 August 2016|work=MelbourneFC.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> His time in the VFL saw him qualify for the finals, and he played in the winning preliminary final against {{VFL Wil}} in which he was stretchered off in the second quarter after losing consciousness from a tackle where his head hit the ground heavily.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/afl/afl-news/melbourne-demon-christian-salem-knocked-out-in-vfl-preliminary-final-for-casey-20160918-grizg7.html|title=Melbourne Demon Christian Salem knocked out in VFL preliminary final for Casey|last=Cherny|first=Daniel|date=18 September 2016|work=The Age|publisher=Fairfax Media|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> He subsequently missed the grand final, in which Casey lost to {{VFL Foo}} by thirty-one points at Etihad Stadium.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/teams/melbourne/christian-salem-could-miss-vfl-grand-final-after-being-knocked-out-at-north-port-oval/news-story/aac4a88befa6a9199695c21a54939da4|title=Christian Salem could miss VFL Grand Final after being knocked out at North Port Oval|last=Gardner|first=Gilbert|date=19 September 2016|work=Herald Sun|publisher=News Corp Australia|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>

[[File:Salem handballing away from Fasolo.1.jpg|thumb|250px|Salem handballing away from Collingwood's, [[Alex Fasolo]], during round 12, 2017.]]
During the 2017 preseason, senior coach, [[Simon Goodwin]], earmarked a move into the midfield for Salem in the upcoming season,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2017-02-18/goodwin-has-high-hopes-for-new-recruit-salem|title=Goodwin has high hopes for 'new recruit' Salem|last=Schmook|first=Nathan|date=18 February 2017|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> however, he suffered a mishap during preseason training, in which he received his third concussion in 2016 due to a brick in his backpack hitting his head during a preseason camp in December.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2017-01-25/demon-back-training-after-being-knocked-out-by-brick|title=Demon back training after being knocked out by brick|last=King|first=Travis|date=25 January 2017|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> Despite the injury, he returned to full fitness in time for the start of the season and played in the opening round match against St Kilda at Etihad Stadium.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.melbournefc.com.au/news/2017-03-23/four-new-players-named-for-round-one|title=Four new players named for round one|last=Burgan|first=Matt|date=23 March 2017|work=MelbourneFC.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> The next week in the twenty-two point win against Carlton at the Melbourne Cricket Ground, he recorded a career-high thirty-one disposals, in addition to seven marks, seven rebound 50s, three tackles and a goal, to be named the best player on the field by AFL Media journalist, Ben Collins.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2017-04-02/salem-optimistic-about-the-year-ahead|title=Career-best game leaves Salem full of optimism|last=Collins|first=Ben|date=2 April 2017|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> In what was labelled his breakthrough game by ''Herald Sun'' reporter, Jay Clark,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.townsvillebulletin.com.au/sport/afl/melbourne-defeat-carlton-at-the-mcg-as-christian-salem-and-clayton-oliver-showcase-demons-future/news-story/3830f0d51214b8879b946f2b6f8679d0|title=Melbourne defeat Carlton at the MCG as Christian Salem and Clayton Oliver showcase Demons’ future|last=Clark|first=Jay|date=2 April 2017|work=Herald Sun|publisher=News Corp Australia|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> he received the maximum three [[Brownlow Medal]] votes, meaning he was adjudged the best player on the ground by the [[Umpire (Australian rules football)|field umpires]].<ref name=afltables/> 

Salem played the first nine matches of the season, until he was suspended for the round ten match against {{AFL GC}} at [[Traeger Park|TIO Traeger Park]] due to striking {{AFL NM}}'s, [[Shaun Higgins]], in the fourteen point loss the week before.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/afl/afl-news/i-dont-like-players-punching-says-afl-ceo-gillon-mclachlan-after-fiery-round-20170522-gwa7ws.html|title=MRP offers ban to Melbourne Demon Christian Salem for elbowing North's Shaun Higgins|last=Colangelo|first=Anthony|date=22 May 2017|work=The Age|publisher=Fairfax Media|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> He received high praise from the media during the first half of the season, with ''[[The Age]]'' journalist, Chloe Saltau, writing Salem's "polish and calm" was a key reason behind Melbourne's improved form,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/afl/afl-news/christian-salem-at-the-heart-of-demons-rebuild--brick-by-brick-20170506-gvzm6m.html|title=Christian Salem at the heart of Demons' rebuild - brick by brick|last=Saltau|first=Chloe|date=6 May 2017|work=The Age|publisher=Fairfax Media|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> Fox Sport Australia's, Anna Harington, noted he was enjoying a breakout season and his elite kicking was a "valuable asset" to Melbourne,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/christian-salem-opens-up-on-his-involvement-in-the-josh-kelly-trade-and-his-2017-breakout-season/news-story/32165164f083e20491c2ee590b1e9fe9|title=Christian Salem opens up on his involvement in the Josh Kelly trade and his 2017 breakout season|last=Harrington|first=Anna|date=20 June 2017|work=Fox Sports (Australia)|publisher=News Corp Australia|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> and AFL Media reporter, Ben Guthrie, reiterated by stating his "elite ball use and composure under pressure [was] proving to be an important component of Melbourne's side."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2017-06-23/dees-lock-in-classy-defender-salem-for-two-more-years|title=Dees lock in classy defender for two more years|last=Guthrie|first=Ben|date=23 June 2017|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> Furthermore, he was named in AFL Media's team of the week for his performances in the round two match against Carlton and the round thirteen match against the Western Bulldogs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2017-04-04/team-of-the-week-r2-did-we-get-it-right|title=Team of the week, R2: Did we get it right?|last=Phelan|first=Jennifer|date=4 April 2017|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2017-06-20/team-of-the-week-r13-did-we-get-it-right|title=Team of the week, R13: Did we get it right?|last1=Phelan|first1=Jennifer|last2=Stephens|first2=Romy|date=20 June 2017|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> 

Missing just the one match from rounds one to fourteen, Salem was forced to miss four weeks of football after sustaining a hamstring injury during the three-point win against {{AFL WC}} at [[Subiaco Oval|Domain Stadium]] in round fourteen.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2017-06-26/blow-for-demons-with-defender-hamstrung|title=Blow for Demons with defender hamstrung|last=Navaratnam|first=Dinny|date=26 June 2017|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> He returned for the twenty-three point win against {{AFL PA}} at the Melbourne Cricket Ground in round eighteen,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/afl-teams-round-18-full-squads-for-every-game-ins-and-outs-injuries-supercoach-advice/news-story/ec38812e33fcaf7bdaebddfc7194e364|title=AFL Teams Round 18: Full squads for every game, ins and outs, injuries, SuperCoach advice|date=21 July 2017|work=Fox Sports (Australia)|publisher=News Corp Australia|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> and played three matches before he was omitted for the round twenty-one match against St Kilda at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2017-08-10/round-21-teams-revealed|title=Big Power outage, Demons dump defenders|last=McGowan|first=Marc|date=10 August 2017|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> The same weekend when he was playing in the VFL, he was suspended for one week for striking Carlton forward, [[Liam Sumner]], thus ruling him ineligible for selection for the round twenty-two match against {{AFL BL2}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2017-08-15/demon-christian-salem-offered-ban-for-striking-in-vfl|title=Demoted Dee accepts ban for striking in VFL|last=Guthrie|first=Ben|date=15 August 2017|work=AFL.com.au|publisher=Bigpond|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> He returned for the final round match against {{AFL Col}} at the Melbourne Cricket Ground and finished with sixteen matches for the season.<ref name=afltables/>

